ional studies of literary works as they are generated over time by authors, editors, typographers, book designers, marketing planners, and other publishing agents. This enables him to examine issues of textual stability and instability in the arenas of textual production and reproduction. Drawing on literary examples from the past two centuries--including works by Byron, Blake, Morris, Yeats, Joyce, and especially Pound--McGann applies his theory to key problems facing anyone who studies texts and textuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexCriticism, Textual. 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aCriticism, Textual. 0aEditing. 0aEnglish literaturexCriticism, Textual. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aTransmission of texts. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aBlake, William.  aBoni and Liveright.  aBowers, Fredson.  aColeridge, S. T.  aDe Man, Paul.  aDickens, Charles.  aEspey, John.  aFaber and Faber.  aGabler, Hans.  aHours Pres.  aJones, Sir William.  aKelmscott Press.  aLachmann, Karl.  aMilford, H. S.  aMorris, William.  aNew Directions.  aOvid Press.  aParker, Hershel.  aPater, Walter.  aPre-Raphaelitism.  aRainey, Lawrence.  aRay, Gordon N.  aShakespeare, William.  aShillingsburg, Peter.  aSwinburne, A. C.  aTanselle, G. Thomas.  aTillotson, Kathleen.  aUnger, Roberto.  aVarela, Francisco.  aWittgenstein, Ludwig.  aYeats, William Butler.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691217758zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691217758423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691217758